<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n18105i"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n18" href="#n18105i">N18 (VI.B.8)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n18all.htm#n18105i"> 105(i)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> ~ censor 312, Capua / Brindisi </blockquote> <dd class="well"><mm class="note">Note: The VIA APPIA, the Great South Road, was commenced by Appius Claudius Caecus, when Censor (ca. 312 <year>B.C.</year>), and has always been the most celebrated of the the Roman Ways. It was the first ever laid down on a grand scale and upon scientific principles, the natural obstacles which it was necessary to overcome were of the most formidable nature, and when completed it well deserved the title of <i>Queen of Roads</i> (<i>regina viarum</i>). It issued from the <i>Porta Capena</i> and originally terminated at <i>Capua</i>, and had seven principal ramifications. It was eventually extended to <i>Brundusium</i>. </mm> </dd></dl>
